03:06.798 --> 03:09.267
[heart beating]

03:11.897 --> 03:14.599
<i>FLINT: "And the Lord said unto Rebecca,</i>

03:14.600 --> 03:17.601
<i>"two nations are in thy womb.</i>

03:25.878 --> 03:29.313
<i>"Two peoples within you
who shall be divided.</i>

03:35.354 --> 03:38.522
<i>"One shall be stronger than the other.</i>

03:44.764 --> 03:47.698
<i>"And the older shall serve the younger."</i>

03:57.777 --> 04:00.779
<i>Twins...</i>

04:00.780 --> 04:04.516
as close as two things can
get to being the same one,

04:04.517 --> 04:07.752
and what's the first thing
they do to each other?

04:07.753 --> 04:10.755
Fight over who gets to be the first one

04:10.756 --> 04:13.156
to see the light of day.

04:14.994 --> 04:17.896
And here I sit at the
head of an army of men,

04:17.897 --> 04:21.332
each of whom, present company included,

04:21.333 --> 04:23.268
has probably at some point considered

04:23.269 --> 04:26.371
killing the man he now fights alongside,

04:26.372 --> 04:28.640
each of whom, present company included,

04:28.641 --> 04:31.743
has certainly considered killing me.

04:31.744 --> 04:33.878
If it makes you feel any better,

04:33.879 --> 04:36.446
I haven't considered
killing you in months.

04:37.349 --> 04:38.982
A little bit.

04:41.587 --> 04:43.286
We're so close.

04:46.258 --> 04:48.425
So very close.

04:50.463 --> 04:52.530
If we can just hold
this alliance together

04:52.531 --> 04:55.533
just a little longer, if we can just...

04:55.558 --> 04:57.511
will it forward just a little more...

04:57.536 --> 05:00.737
And nothing will ever be the
same for anyone ever again.

05:04.110 --> 05:06.611
You and I have willed our
men through unthinkable things

05:06.612 --> 05:08.478
to get this far.

05:09.448 --> 05:11.916
Why not one more?

05:11.941 --> 05:14.241
To call Nassau home again.

05:16.422 --> 05:19.689
- [bell ringing]
- <i>MAN: Two flags on the starboard bow!</i>

05:26.574 --> 05:29.410
- [waves crashing]
- [men chattering]

05:29.435 --> 05:32.303
There's no sign of
the alarm being raised.

05:32.304 --> 05:34.105
Is it possible they
trust our false colors?

05:34.106 --> 05:37.642
Well, anything's possible,
but I wouldn't count on it.

05:37.843 --> 05:41.746
Maintain our current
approach, present heading.

05:41.747 --> 05:43.114
<i>Prepare to take courses.</i>

05:43.115 --> 05:44.969
<i>DE GROOT: Aye, Captain.</i>

05:44.994 --> 05:46.407
<i>Maintain course.</i>

05:47.553 --> 05:49.354
<i>MAN: All hands, stand
by to change course.</i>

05:49.355 --> 05:51.890
Lookout reports had
five two-masted vessels

05:51.891 --> 05:54.125
in the harbor while you were below.

05:54.126 --> 05:56.661
That's what Billy's information
suggested we should expect.

05:56.662 --> 05:59.130
<i>DE GROOT: I want more men in the yard.</i>

05:59.131 --> 06:00.765
With the governor's naval consort gone

06:00.766 --> 06:03.635
and the fort lightly armed, if at all,

06:03.971 --> 06:06.571
they won't be able to prevent
us from making our landing today.

06:06.572 --> 06:08.273
Hmm.

06:08.274 --> 06:10.107
<i>DE GROOT: Keep the course.</i>

06:11.689 --> 06:13.255
Stay with the land.

06:13.846 --> 06:15.814
You still don't trust him, do you?

06:15.815 --> 06:18.049
I understand why you do.

06:18.050 --> 06:20.418
I don't believe that's what I asked.

06:20.419 --> 06:23.954
I don't believe you want me
to answer what you've asked.

06:24.824 --> 06:27.826
We are in sight of the
end of this journey,

06:27.827 --> 06:30.128
and he's still worried this
alliance all falls apart

06:30.129 --> 06:32.068
before we get there.

06:32.765 --> 06:34.199
Please don't give him any more reason

06:34.200 --> 06:36.633
to indulge that feeling.

06:39.379 --> 06:42.473
♪ ♪

06:50.883 --> 06:54.118
Gun crews, prepare the
starboard batteries, double shot!

06:54.119 --> 06:55.353
Sharpen up the yards now.

06:55.354 --> 06:58.456
And clew our courses as
we approach the harbor.

06:58.457 --> 06:59.891
Helm, once we've cleared the reefs,

06:59.892 --> 07:01.726
head up two points so that
we might begin our run.

07:01.727 --> 07:03.126
Aye, sir.

07:04.188 --> 07:07.329
[men shouting indistinctly]

07:10.302 --> 07:12.303
One of us should probably say something.

07:12.304 --> 07:14.873
About what?

07:14.874 --> 07:17.442
I don't know, the moment?

07:17.443 --> 07:21.312
Remind the men in whose name
this fight is to be fought?

07:21.313 --> 07:23.280
You think they've forgotten?

07:24.383 --> 07:28.419
No, but we are emotional
beings, after all,

07:28.420 --> 07:32.154
and rhetoric is the
fuel that feeds the fire.

07:32.791 --> 07:35.526
For 10,000 years, a man
anticipating conquest

07:35.527 --> 07:37.727
- has stood before his army...
- Do it.

07:47.106 --> 07:51.284
Friends, a word before it all begins.

07:51.309 --> 07:53.077
It's no wonder you don't say much.

07:53.102 --> 07:54.712
<i>RACKHAM: If you please.</i>

07:54.713 --> 07:56.581
<i>MAN: Lads, hey, listen up.</i>

07:56.582 --> 07:57.896
- [chatter stops]
- <i>RACKHAM: Thank you.</i>

07:58.584 --> 08:02.553
All of us have given
some part of ourselves

08:02.554 --> 08:04.889
to reach this moment.

08:04.890 --> 08:07.857
Today, we reclaim what is ours.

08:10.562 --> 08:14.799
And we seek retribution
for what was taken from us.

08:14.800 --> 08:18.368
Today there will be vengeance
for the death of Charles Vane.

08:19.855 --> 08:23.073
♪ ♪

08:35.321 --> 08:36.821
<i>SILVER: What is it?</i>

08:36.822 --> 08:39.256
<i>FLINT: The governor's
sloops aren't moving.</i>

08:39.258 --> 08:41.732
Well, what would you have them doing?

08:42.561 --> 08:46.162
Outgunned as they are, maybe nothing.

08:47.732 --> 08:49.665
Maybe something.

08:50.869 --> 08:53.438
What the hell does that mean?

08:53.439 --> 08:55.905
<i>DE GROOT: The Revenge is
almost in range of the fort.</i>

09:00.980 --> 09:02.888
No guns.

09:03.896 --> 09:06.196
It's just as Billy said.

09:07.654 --> 09:10.420
[men shouting indistinctly]

09:12.524 --> 09:14.125
Standby the anchor!

09:14.126 --> 09:16.527
And signal the Eagle to
offer her larboard batteries

09:16.552 --> 09:18.238
to hold those sloops at bay.

09:18.263 --> 09:20.163
- [men shouting orders]
- What the fuck is the Defiant doing?

09:22.451 --> 09:24.502
Why is she cutting across our bow?

09:24.503 --> 09:26.237
MAN: The Defiant's altering course!

09:26.238 --> 09:28.639
Helm! Hard to starboard!

09:28.640 --> 09:29.640
Hard over!

09:29.641 --> 09:30.866
- Trim in all the sails!
- [all shouting]

09:30.891 --> 09:32.499
Brace up sharp!

09:32.586 --> 09:35.625
♪ ♪

09:43.877 --> 09:46.385
[wood creaking, cracking]

09:51.052 --> 09:54.521
<i>MAN: Take the larboard bow! Move ahead!</i>

09:55.418 --> 09:59.059
- [men shouting]
- [wood creaking]

10:00.906 --> 10:04.409
- Let the sheets fly!
- Let the sheets fly!

10:04.410 --> 10:06.976
<i>MAN: Let the sheets fly!</i>

10:15.195 --> 10:17.554
[wood cracking, groaning]

10:22.273 --> 10:24.913
[men shouting]

10:25.431 --> 10:26.696
<i>Man #1: Let go of the line!</i>

10:26.721 --> 10:28.166
<i>Man #2: Watch out for the cannons!</i>

10:28.167 --> 10:31.207
- [men shouting]
- MAN: Look out! Brace yourselves!

10:31.603 --> 10:33.236
<i>SILVER: Can we get free?</i>

10:35.212 --> 10:37.134
[all shouting]

10:37.755 --> 10:39.788
<i>Get to the guns!</i>

10:41.518 --> 10:43.047
Get the shots!

10:43.048 --> 10:45.716
<i>BERRINGER: Looks like
the barricade held, sir.</i>

10:45.717 --> 10:47.385
<i>Your orders?</i>

10:47.859 --> 10:49.153
Open fire.

10:49.154 --> 10:51.956
Eastern battery, open fire.

10:51.957 --> 10:54.225
<i>- Man #1: Fire!
- Man #2: Fire!</i>

10:54.226 --> 10:55.959
Take cover!

10:57.362 --> 10:58.784
[man screaming]

10:58.809 --> 11:01.076
<i>- Man #1: Fire!
- Man #2: Fire!</i>

11:03.655 --> 11:04.679
[wood groans]

11:04.703 --> 11:06.077
<i>MAN: Brace ahead!</i>

11:06.102 --> 11:07.164
[groans]

11:15.538 --> 11:18.007
[men screaming]

11:20.562 --> 11:23.203
[screaming]

11:24.289 --> 11:26.324
Signal the sloops to engage.

11:26.325 --> 11:27.792
Engage the sloops!

11:27.793 --> 11:30.126
<i>MAN: Signal to pursue!</i>

11:30.973 --> 11:33.020
[men shouting]

11:38.837 --> 11:40.134
[cannonballs crashing]

11:42.174 --> 11:43.741
I'm giving the order!

11:43.742 --> 11:45.510
Not yet.

11:45.511 --> 11:48.278
If we don't get these men
off the ship, they're dead.

11:48.303 --> 11:51.249
If we don't find a way to harass
those guns, everyone's dead.

11:51.250 --> 11:52.950
Harass them with what?

11:52.951 --> 11:54.652
The starboard guns can't elevate enough

11:54.653 --> 11:56.059
to get anywhere near that fort.

11:56.122 --> 11:57.630
- [cannonballs crashing]
- [grunts]

11:57.809 --> 11:59.621
[men shouting]

12:02.494 --> 12:04.710
- All hands!
- [man screaming]

12:04.735 --> 12:07.383
Reset the topsails and t'gallants!

12:07.408 --> 12:09.211
- [men shouting]
- [cannonballs crashing]

12:09.236 --> 12:10.268
Now!

12:10.269 --> 12:12.284
<i>MAN: Ready top sails!</i>

12:14.506 --> 12:15.973
Ready those guns!

12:15.974 --> 12:18.776
[Crashing and screaming continue]

12:18.777 --> 12:20.611
T'gallants!

12:20.636 --> 12:23.038
- Pull! Pull! <i>
- MAN: Put your backs into it!</i>

12:23.336 --> 12:24.549
Pull those lines!

12:24.550 --> 12:27.417
Pull! Pull!

12:43.078 --> 12:45.236
<i>Man #1: Top sails in the corner.</i>

12:45.237 --> 12:46.742
<i>Man #2: Top sails!</i>

12:48.679 --> 12:51.051
Reload with chain shot
and target their canvas.

12:51.076 --> 12:53.176
- <i>MAN: Reload with chain shot!</i>
- Go!

12:54.179 --> 12:56.013
<i>MAN: Fire!</i>

12:56.476 --> 12:58.015
[cannons firing]

13:02.827 --> 13:04.483
[screams]

13:09.061 --> 13:10.928
Gun crews!

13:10.929 --> 13:12.788
On my mark!

13:15.069 --> 13:16.944
[cannonball crashes]

13:17.397 --> 13:18.896
Fire!

13:20.447 --> 13:21.853
[men shout]

13:27.598 --> 13:28.993
Ah!

13:29.668 --> 13:31.637
[cannon fire continues]

13:34.086 --> 13:37.086
Abandon ship! All hands!

13:37.111 --> 13:39.534
[men shouting]

13:41.706 --> 13:43.894
<i>FLINT: Abandon ship!</i>

13:43.895 --> 13:45.395
Get the ladders over!

13:45.420 --> 13:46.730
[men shouting]

13:47.590 --> 13:49.871
[all screaming]

13:55.989 --> 13:58.981
[cannonballs crashing]

14:09.288 --> 14:10.421
Get on the longboats.

14:10.422 --> 14:11.789
What are you doing?

14:11.790 --> 14:13.057
I'll be the slowest one.

14:13.058 --> 14:14.625
Get on the ladder!

14:14.626 --> 14:16.756
It's all right. Go.

14:16.881 --> 14:17.957
[screams]

14:17.982 --> 14:19.070
Go!

14:27.544 --> 14:29.677
Why aren't we moving in closer?

14:32.210 --> 14:34.111
We cannot fire the great
guns into that mess.

14:34.112 --> 14:35.646
We'll kill as many of
our own men as theirs.

14:35.647 --> 14:37.248
But if we run with the one ship

14:37.249 --> 14:38.749
that still presents a
threat to the governor,

14:38.750 --> 14:40.851
he may very well chase

14:40.852 --> 14:42.887
and give the survivors
their best chance of escaping

14:42.888 --> 14:45.489
to the fallback position
on the eastern shore.

14:45.490 --> 14:47.457
And if they don't chase?

14:49.053 --> 14:51.576
- [cannonball crashes]
- [screams]

14:52.521 --> 14:54.357
[men screaming]

15:00.503 --> 15:01.870
[man screams]

15:02.507 --> 15:04.575
Come on! Get in the longboat!

15:04.576 --> 15:05.843
I got ya!

15:12.951 --> 15:15.353
<i>[Cannonball whistles, crashes]</i>

15:15.354 --> 15:16.664
Fall, sir!

15:18.290 --> 15:19.899
<i>MAN: We're not gonna make it!</i>

15:19.924 --> 15:21.133
[gasps]

15:24.461 --> 15:26.781
[muffled shouting]

15:31.447 --> 15:33.572
[gunfire]

15:34.697 --> 15:37.283
[muffled sounds echoing]

15:47.866 --> 15:49.803
- [bullets whistling]
- [gasps]

15:52.889 --> 15:56.381
♪ ♪

16:12.377 --> 16:15.211
[faint] Return fire!

16:18.083 --> 16:19.816
In the wind!

16:21.560 --> 16:23.653
[no audible dialogue]

16:27.755 --> 16:31.286
[ship creaking and groaning]

16:41.206 --> 16:43.541
<i>BERRINGER: Shall we pursue
the man-of-war, my Lord?</i>

16:43.960 --> 16:46.110
It'd be the cost of
rounding up those longboats.

16:46.111 --> 16:48.179
Are you certain your
men can capture her?

16:48.180 --> 16:50.587
Teach is a formidable opponent,

16:50.612 --> 16:53.317
but his ship is weakened, and my
men can attack from three directions

16:53.318 --> 16:55.923
with greater numbers
with greater discipline.

16:56.521 --> 16:58.877
Tactically, he's greatly disadvantaged.

16:58.902 --> 17:02.026
Between tactics and passion,
I'll take the latter.

17:02.027 --> 17:03.761
If our information's
correct and he seeks revenge

17:03.762 --> 17:05.195
over the death of Charles Vane,

17:05.196 --> 17:06.931
he will fight with passion today.

17:06.932 --> 17:10.067
Revenge is a powerful
motivator, undoubtedly.

17:10.068 --> 17:11.669
Fortunately, my men would like

17:11.670 --> 17:13.903
a little of it for themselves as well.

17:16.781 --> 17:18.509
Do it.

17:18.510 --> 17:20.444
Signal to pursue!

17:21.233 --> 17:23.785
Inform the council I'll return
once the street is secure.

17:25.172 --> 17:26.839
And please have someone
retrieve my wife.

17:26.865 --> 17:28.898
<i>Of course, my Lord.</i>

17:29.688 --> 17:32.989
[Soft conversations, baby crying]

17:34.258 --> 17:37.008
[priest reading Bible verses]

17:57.249 --> 17:58.966
Oh, fuck.

17:58.991 --> 18:00.569
[groans]

18:03.895 --> 18:06.195
<i>MAX: It has been quiet for some time.</i>

18:07.926 --> 18:10.127
Is that bad for us or bad for them?

18:10.128 --> 18:12.029
Hard to say.

18:13.006 --> 18:15.737
If it were bad for us, I
assume we would know by now.

18:17.747 --> 18:19.814
For whose benefit is that?

18:20.939 --> 18:24.558
I'm told that once mastered,
it's actually quite soothing.

18:25.107 --> 18:27.855
At this moment, I'm finding
that hard to believe.

18:30.215 --> 18:32.182
But if I am to play the role,

18:32.183 --> 18:34.450
I ought to make some
effort to look the part.

18:35.453 --> 18:38.222
It bothers me that this
does not bother you.

18:38.882 --> 18:40.591
What's that?

18:40.960 --> 18:43.327
This. That.

18:43.328 --> 18:44.827
All of it.

18:47.098 --> 18:51.068
The world is changing so
rapidly and we with it.

18:51.069 --> 18:52.403
I fear the day will soon come

18:52.404 --> 18:54.445
when we will no longer recognize either.

18:54.470 --> 18:55.609
[chuckles softly]

18:55.634 --> 18:57.387
We are who we are.

18:57.412 --> 19:00.012
Nothing so important changes so quickly.

19:00.037 --> 19:01.189
[door opens]

19:03.743 --> 19:05.349
Mrs. Rogers?

19:05.350 --> 19:07.587
The governor requests your presence.

19:13.310 --> 19:15.732
[indistinct conversations]

19:31.937 --> 19:34.545
Two ships grounded and only
one escaped the barricade.

19:35.147 --> 19:37.248
Three ships grounded.

19:37.273 --> 19:39.010
Teach is still loose.

19:40.258 --> 19:42.947
All things considered,
we are very lucky.

19:45.319 --> 19:47.720
I'm sorry you weren't there to see it.

19:47.745 --> 19:50.561
I know it cannot be
comfortable to be so removed.

19:50.562 --> 19:52.763
I don't know.

19:52.764 --> 19:54.697
I got to make this.

20:01.157 --> 20:02.773
I am sure there were
others that found themselves

20:02.774 --> 20:05.109
more uncomfortable today than I.

20:05.134 --> 20:07.282
<i>MAN: Company at the ready!</i>

20:07.307 --> 20:08.491
<i>Company!</i>

20:08.516 --> 20:10.714
And I told you before we
ever set foot on this island

20:10.715 --> 20:14.184
I will do whatever necessary
to ensure your success here.

20:14.185 --> 20:15.986
If the street understands
us better when I sit

20:15.987 --> 20:18.489
among your men's wives
rather than your men,

20:18.490 --> 20:20.624
if the world makes more
sense to them that way

20:20.625 --> 20:22.572
and your authority grows because of it,

20:22.597 --> 20:24.094
as uncomfortable as it may be,

20:24.119 --> 20:26.972
then that is a compromise
I am willing to make.

20:29.782 --> 20:31.348
<i>MAN: Governor?</i>

20:36.675 --> 20:38.308
I'll send for you as
soon as I'm satisfied

20:38.309 --> 20:39.976
the street is secure.

20:44.634 --> 20:46.301
Captain.

20:46.368 --> 20:49.735
♪ ♪

21:01.256 --> 21:03.123
<i>FLINT: That's the last one.</i>

21:05.403 --> 21:08.072
According to the men who just landed,

21:08.073 --> 21:10.006
that is the last longboat.

21:12.389 --> 21:14.188
I heard the same.

21:16.225 --> 21:18.881
I'm told they saw an injured man

21:18.906 --> 21:21.506
pulled aboard from out of the water,

21:21.531 --> 21:23.326
almost drowned.

21:23.988 --> 21:25.688
I heard the same.

21:32.363 --> 21:35.265
Here I must be careful.

21:35.266 --> 21:39.536
I have well over 200
men unaccounted for.

21:40.170 --> 21:42.339
Those who remain, it will be very hard

21:42.340 --> 21:44.274
to explain to them why,

21:44.592 --> 21:48.545
with all I have to attend
to, I choose to stand here

21:48.749 --> 21:51.650
hanging onto the fate
of just one of them.

21:54.452 --> 21:56.086
I know that you and he

21:56.087 --> 21:58.789
had been working
closely together of late,

21:58.790 --> 22:01.023
become friends even.

22:04.806 --> 22:07.006
I don't know what I'm trying to say.

22:10.061 --> 22:12.217
Perhaps just that...

22:12.429 --> 22:14.396
he is my friend, too.

22:41.590 --> 22:43.121
[sharp whistle]

22:48.106 --> 22:50.107
- They obstructed the harbor!
- I know.

22:50.108 --> 22:51.475
Two ships they sunk!

22:51.476 --> 22:52.936
It must have taken them days to arrange!

22:52.961 --> 22:55.241
<i>- I know, I...</i>
- Then why the fuck didn't you warn us?!

22:55.266 --> 22:57.147
I did warn you!

22:57.772 --> 23:00.083
There were three ships, not two.

23:00.084 --> 23:01.518
He bought them cheap out of Abaco.

23:01.519 --> 23:03.353
He scuttled them six days ago.

23:03.659 --> 23:06.123
The moment I learned of it, I
sent word to Mr. Featherstone.

23:06.124 --> 23:09.658
He was supposed to send word
to you not to enter the harbor.

23:10.961 --> 23:13.230
Then Mr. Featherstone has fucked us all.

23:13.231 --> 23:15.097
Yes, I know that, too.

23:20.236 --> 23:22.103
Is this all that's left?

23:24.856 --> 23:27.344
Teach and <i> the Revenge</i>
are unaccounted for.

23:28.426 --> 23:30.345
<i>I saw them sailing north</i>

23:30.370 --> 23:32.870
<i>away from the harbor under pursuit.</i>

23:34.452 --> 23:36.395
The rest...

23:37.169 --> 23:39.803
are presumed dead or captured.

23:42.525 --> 23:44.224
And Silver?

23:45.261 --> 23:47.061
Which is he?

24:04.015 --> 24:06.350
There'll be debts to repay after today.

24:06.351 --> 24:09.019
And there'll be plenty of time to do it.

24:09.956 --> 24:12.638
But right now, we need
to get off the sand.

24:23.268 --> 24:24.967
<i>MADI: Where are you?</i>

24:31.476 --> 24:33.097
What?

24:33.122 --> 24:35.679
We sail for Nassau soon.

24:36.700 --> 24:38.615
There are many other places I could be

24:38.616 --> 24:41.652
in this moment to prepare.

24:41.653 --> 24:43.752
I choose to be here.

24:45.056 --> 24:47.056
Where have you just chosen to go?

24:50.295 --> 24:53.533
We received word today from Nassau

24:54.098 --> 24:57.467
that Billy's resistance movement
has proclaimed its fealty

24:57.468 --> 24:59.840
to a pirate king,

25:01.106 --> 25:05.247
a man who would one day return
to Nassau from his exile,

25:05.272 --> 25:08.011
expel the English,

25:08.012 --> 25:10.879
and punish those who betrayed the cause.

25:13.997 --> 25:17.331
You left my bed for that?

25:18.423 --> 25:21.491
Now, the pirate king's name...

25:21.874 --> 25:24.375
is Long John Silver.

25:28.110 --> 25:31.101
Long John Silver?

25:31.102 --> 25:32.468
Yeah.

25:35.827 --> 25:38.594
Who is long John Silver?

25:40.678 --> 25:43.813
Well, that's a very good question.

25:44.549 --> 25:47.117
I assume he saw value in the tall tales

25:47.118 --> 25:50.153
told about me after
that night in the tavern.

25:50.319 --> 25:53.023
Saw mystery in it, perhaps.

25:53.024 --> 25:55.758
Use my name upon which
to build his story.

25:57.628 --> 26:00.963
And this bothers you why?

26:02.897 --> 26:06.750
We've come this far because when
Flint and I are of the same mind,

26:06.775 --> 26:10.540
there's no obstacle yet
encountered that we cannot surmount.

26:10.812 --> 26:13.085
I don't know why that is.

26:13.110 --> 26:15.545
He doesn't know why it is.

26:15.795 --> 26:17.795
But it is.

26:18.950 --> 26:20.751
To elevate one of us over the other,

26:20.752 --> 26:22.777
even as a fiction,

26:23.733 --> 26:27.901
seems to me to be tempting
fate in a most dangerous way.

26:28.659 --> 26:30.526
And...

26:33.398 --> 26:37.933
And it upsets you because
you believe he is your friend?

26:40.071 --> 26:42.572
Yes, it upsets me.

26:42.573 --> 26:44.508
And I know that Billy's
been looking for a way

26:44.509 --> 26:47.377
to remove Flint from
our lives for months now.

26:47.378 --> 26:49.646
I'm sure that's somewhere
at the root of this.

26:49.647 --> 26:52.107
And I don't like having him
conscripting me into his cause

26:52.132 --> 26:54.207
without me even having a say.

26:57.321 --> 26:58.789
I'm sorry.

26:59.326 --> 27:03.058
Because I <i> believe</i> he is my friend?

27:04.529 --> 27:06.229
Are you questioning
whether I'm qualified

27:06.230 --> 27:08.497
to have an opinion on that subject?

27:10.976 --> 27:14.304
Did you not once tell me of your worry

27:14.305 --> 27:16.006
about the fate of those

27:16.007 --> 27:18.708
whom Captain Flint has
called friends before you?

27:19.000 --> 27:20.977
A lot has changed since then.

27:20.978 --> 27:25.082
A lot <i> has</i> changed since
then, but what has not changed

27:25.083 --> 27:27.551
is that when a man first needs you

27:27.552 --> 27:30.687
and thereafter calls you a friend,

27:30.688 --> 27:34.391
a little suspicion is a healthy thing.

27:35.012 --> 27:37.694
That'd make a lot more
sense if I didn't need him

27:37.695 --> 27:39.426
just as badly as he needs me.

27:39.451 --> 27:41.731
I don't believe you do.

27:42.433 --> 27:46.217
Whatever he is to you,
whatever you are to him...

27:47.171 --> 27:50.572
I don't believe you need
him to be the man you are.

27:53.420 --> 27:56.145
I think you would be a very good king.

27:58.827 --> 28:01.651
If I were a no-good pirate,

28:01.886 --> 28:04.387
I would follow you wherever you led.

28:17.087 --> 28:20.923
♪ ♪

28:43.022 --> 28:45.589
[Cannon fire, men shouting]

28:49.634 --> 28:53.270
Take the courses. Brace
the main and mizzen aback.

28:53.271 --> 28:55.693
Haul in the guns.
Close all the gun ports.

28:55.718 --> 28:56.907
You're letting up?

28:56.908 --> 28:58.642
With the damage done to the rig,

28:58.643 --> 29:01.765
I can't maneuver our broadside around
fast enough to be of any effect.

29:02.101 --> 29:03.537
The sloops are too nimble.

29:03.562 --> 29:05.680
But hauling in the guns?

29:05.705 --> 29:07.150
They'll board us easily.

29:07.175 --> 29:09.640
I was always told that you
were the one without fear.

29:09.665 --> 29:11.172
Was I misinformed?

29:11.197 --> 29:14.432
It ain't fear to want
to do a hard thing smart.

29:22.745 --> 29:24.878
He wants this fight.

29:25.777 --> 29:27.343
Let him have it.

29:29.884 --> 29:31.241
Prepare to be boarded!

29:31.242 --> 29:33.375
<i>MAN: Prepare to be boarded!</i>

29:37.829 --> 29:39.563
[men shouting]

29:47.440 --> 29:48.799
[swords clashing]

29:52.417 --> 29:53.815
[grunting angrily]

30:56.027 --> 30:58.473
My Lord,

30:58.498 --> 31:01.160
the squad is returning
from the outer beaches.

31:01.430 --> 31:04.964
All told, the captives number 75.

31:06.070 --> 31:08.571
Well, there are more
out there. There must be.

31:08.572 --> 31:10.206
With our numbers, our ability to search

31:10.207 --> 31:12.509
outside Nassau town is limited.

31:12.510 --> 31:14.344
Without any sense of where to look...

31:14.345 --> 31:15.982
And what about informants?

31:16.007 --> 31:18.365
[scoffs] Informants?

31:18.783 --> 31:20.617
Well, there must be
someone in town who knows

31:20.618 --> 31:22.519
where the pirates would go to hide.

31:23.092 --> 31:25.481
I understand they might be
hesitant to come forward yesterday,

31:25.482 --> 31:28.634
with the outcome in doubt, but today?

31:28.659 --> 31:30.360
Are you telling me that literally no one

31:30.361 --> 31:32.194
has offered assistance?

31:34.681 --> 31:36.228
[chuckles]

31:37.268 --> 31:39.202
Oh, of course they haven't.

31:39.203 --> 31:41.338
Why would they when it is so much easier

31:41.339 --> 31:42.795
to do nothing at all?

31:43.576 --> 31:45.108
Somewhere on the other
side of the world,

31:45.109 --> 31:46.676
Spain and England are
fighting yet another war

31:46.677 --> 31:49.240
over what king will
sit upon what throne.

31:49.623 --> 31:50.965
Meanwhile we fight an enemy here

31:50.990 --> 31:53.616
determined to see all
of civilization collapse.

31:53.617 --> 31:56.787
The only thing standing between
them and their goal is you and I,

31:56.812 --> 31:59.711
and no one else seems willing
to lift a finger to help.

32:01.392 --> 32:03.460
I hope at some point
someone will explain to me

32:03.485 --> 32:06.053
what sort of sense any of that makes.

32:07.127 --> 32:08.565
<i>MAN: Don't look at me! Keep moving.</i>

32:08.566 --> 32:10.499
You heard, move.

32:11.969 --> 32:13.769
How many others?

32:15.172 --> 32:16.473
On your knees!

32:16.474 --> 32:19.376
Captured nine more just
east of the fence line.

32:19.377 --> 32:22.724
We think this one's
Flint's ship's master.

32:29.958 --> 32:32.365
You are part of Flint's inner circle?

32:33.630 --> 32:37.494
If you have information about
Captain Flint's contingency plans,

32:37.495 --> 32:40.363
it may argue in favor of leniency.

32:41.129 --> 32:42.662
Go fuck yourself.

32:45.467 --> 32:47.133
Pull him up.

32:50.521 --> 32:53.154
You don't remember me, do you?

32:55.936 --> 32:59.749
I was there that day in the forest,

32:59.750 --> 33:02.623
when your trap was sprung.

33:03.287 --> 33:06.523
I saw what your people did to my men.

33:07.184 --> 33:10.716
I was told that after the fact,

33:11.071 --> 33:13.145
the children of the camp...

33:13.170 --> 33:18.130
were encouraged to remove the
ears from men I called friends.

33:19.470 --> 33:23.673
Trophies to mark the victory.

33:23.970 --> 33:27.143
We that remain do so in violation

33:27.144 --> 33:29.759
of our orders to return home,

33:30.414 --> 33:34.382
a breach of our duty
to His Majesty's Army.

33:36.429 --> 33:40.657
Someday, if we see England again,

33:40.658 --> 33:43.593
I imagine we'll have to answer for it.

33:44.266 --> 33:45.679
Hold him.

33:49.400 --> 33:54.002
But some things are
more important than duty.

33:57.341 --> 33:59.474
No, n-no!

33:59.499 --> 34:01.411
[screaming]

34:09.286 --> 34:12.484
I doubt they'll turn on
their own kind, my Lord.

34:12.509 --> 34:15.478
This isn't that sort of a war anymore.

34:20.947 --> 34:24.266
I want the trials started
as soon as possible.

34:24.268 --> 34:26.087
I want this behind us.

34:26.480 --> 34:27.938
Of course.

34:37.348 --> 34:39.282
BILLY: After you defeated his forces,

34:39.283 --> 34:43.097
the naval commander notified the
governor he was quitting Nassau,

34:43.098 --> 34:45.197
took his fleet right to London.

34:45.222 --> 34:48.458
One subordinate, Captain Berringer,

34:48.458 --> 34:50.560
he led a mutiny of a few hundred men

34:50.561 --> 34:53.667
determined to stay and
avenge their defeat.

34:54.297 --> 34:57.534
Swore a loyalty oath
to Rogers personally,

34:57.535 --> 34:59.736
and then began a purge in town of anyone

34:59.737 --> 35:02.805
even suspected of having
a connection to our cause.

35:02.806 --> 35:04.207
What kind of purge?

35:04.208 --> 35:07.310
Well, hangings, torture.

35:07.311 --> 35:09.979
Eventually the street was
more afraid of him than of us,

35:09.980 --> 35:12.348
and the black spots had
ceased having any effect.

35:12.349 --> 35:14.017
So we challenged him directly,

35:14.018 --> 35:16.152
tried to force our way into town, but...

35:16.153 --> 35:17.720
his men are fanatical,

35:17.721 --> 35:20.123
and the fighting was most bloody.

35:20.715 --> 35:25.123
At its worst, Berringer tried to
reach out from town into our camp,

35:25.148 --> 35:27.630
turned two of our men against us,

35:27.851 --> 35:29.904
<i>help finish us off for good.</i>

35:29.929 --> 35:33.319
<i>Fortunately we were able to
discover the plot in time.</i>

35:46.550 --> 35:49.056
The lines are settled now.

35:49.081 --> 35:52.126
He controls the town but little else.

35:52.151 --> 35:54.765
My people have free reign over
most of the rest of the island.

35:54.790 --> 35:56.322
<i>Your</i> people?

35:58.438 --> 35:59.969
[horse whinnies in distance]

36:02.466 --> 36:04.199
The scouts are returning.

36:05.402 --> 36:07.456
I'll meet you inside.

36:07.481 --> 36:11.128
♪ ♪

37:10.078 --> 37:12.281
[indistinct whispering]

37:13.937 --> 37:15.670
<i>MADI: Is it over?</i>

37:19.457 --> 37:21.169
Is what over?

37:22.997 --> 37:24.614
You looked into my mother's eyes

37:24.615 --> 37:27.871
and you said a great
war lay ahead of us,

37:28.952 --> 37:31.954
one in which pirates and
slaves would stand together

37:31.955 --> 37:34.390
and strike a blow that might
shake the very foundation

37:34.391 --> 37:36.424
of the British Empire.

37:37.995 --> 37:40.222
Now our ships are gone,

37:40.247 --> 37:42.959
our army is fractured,

37:42.984 --> 37:46.452
battered, and beaten.

37:47.337 --> 37:50.405
And the only man among
you I trusted is dead.

37:54.144 --> 37:56.294
I'm asking you...

37:56.319 --> 37:58.559
if this war died with him.

38:07.776 --> 38:10.909
MAN: Come down! Open
this door! Get over here!

38:18.592 --> 38:20.224
[men shouting angrily]

38:35.285 --> 38:37.553
<i>MAN: It is the opinion of this court</i>

38:37.554 --> 38:39.589
<i>that the evidence brought to bear</i>

38:39.590 --> 38:41.557
<i>against this particular defendant</i>

38:41.558 --> 38:46.262
<i>is both abundant and incontrovertible.</i>

38:46.831 --> 38:49.665
<i>Having afforded him ample opportunity</i>

38:49.666 --> 38:51.800
<i>to speak in his own defense...</i>

38:53.704 --> 38:56.296
121 prisoners we took today.

38:57.562 --> 38:59.742
Had our enemies 121 prisoners of ours,

38:59.743 --> 39:03.421
I imagine their deaths
would be swift and cruel.

39:04.437 --> 39:09.152
For us, it means 121 prisoners
to be housed and guarded,

39:09.427 --> 39:12.321
121 mouths to feed,

39:12.322 --> 39:15.083
121 trials to process.

39:16.126 --> 39:18.227
Never let it be said
that civilization came

39:18.228 --> 39:20.395
to anyone easily here.

39:23.000 --> 39:25.334
And these trials,

39:25.553 --> 39:28.220
they will all be taking place here?

39:32.429 --> 39:35.964
It would please me if you
would accommodate it, yes.

39:39.366 --> 39:43.286
Judge Adams and his... court,

39:43.287 --> 39:45.555
we have all seen in recent
weeks since their arrival

39:45.556 --> 39:48.324
that their appetites are significant.

39:48.325 --> 39:51.648
Shall I expect to be reimbursed
for the costs of this?

39:55.199 --> 39:57.133
You stood in my office

39:57.134 --> 40:00.403
and said you wished us to be friends.

40:00.404 --> 40:01.704
As my friend, I would think

40:01.705 --> 40:03.206
you would be eager to do your part

40:03.207 --> 40:06.643
to see our common enterprise
survive its current crisis.

40:07.478 --> 40:09.738
I beg your pardon, my Lord,

40:09.763 --> 40:12.548
but have I not proved
to you my friendship?

40:12.549 --> 40:15.751
At great personal risk to
myself and my interests,

40:15.752 --> 40:18.654
I made enemies of the pirates
in order to ensure your success.

40:18.655 --> 40:20.857
<i>Made</i> enemies of them?

40:21.225 --> 40:23.526
They've been my enemies
for some time now.

40:23.527 --> 40:25.094
Are you saying that
they haven't been yours?

40:25.095 --> 40:28.798
- May I suggest...
- I thank you for your aid today.

40:28.799 --> 40:31.400
<i>It is, I believe, to be expected,</i>

40:31.401 --> 40:35.438
today, tomorrow, every
day till the war is won.

40:35.439 --> 40:37.607
That is the burden that
we all ought to share.

40:37.608 --> 40:40.476
I serve you best, my Lord,
when I am seen by the street

40:40.477 --> 40:42.983
as having some independence from you,

40:43.008 --> 40:44.814
as your silent partner, I am able...

40:44.815 --> 40:46.415
There are no silent partners anymore.

40:46.416 --> 40:48.350
I will have no more of them.

40:48.375 --> 40:50.446
This is now an island of true friends

40:50.471 --> 40:52.397
and mortal enemies
and nothing in between.

40:52.422 --> 40:55.558
Now, in this moment, I still
believe you are among the former.

40:56.043 --> 40:59.080
Should I have any reason
to believe otherwise?

41:00.241 --> 41:02.141
Of course not, my Lord.

41:03.400 --> 41:04.500
Thank you.

41:04.501 --> 41:07.135
[Gavel bangs, crowd murmuring]

41:17.318 --> 41:19.418
Give us the room.

41:25.998 --> 41:27.702
I don't have exact numbers,

41:27.727 --> 41:30.286
but it sounds as though there's already
been a significant number of prisoners

41:30.311 --> 41:32.317
captured from the harbor.

41:32.342 --> 41:33.996
I assume they'll push to
start the hangings right away,

41:33.997 --> 41:36.165
which doesn't leave us much time.

41:46.772 --> 41:49.708
Now, even with your men here,
we don't have sufficient numbers

41:49.733 --> 41:52.749
to move on Nassau directly
and be assured victory.

41:54.019 --> 41:57.755
But if we could dramatically
increase those numbers...

41:57.756 --> 41:59.557
Increase them how?

41:59.558 --> 42:01.860
The Underhill plantation.

42:02.264 --> 42:04.896
It's the largest and richest
of the interior estates,

42:04.897 --> 42:09.300
and it's home to well over 200 slaves.

42:09.301 --> 42:11.253
It's well-defended.

42:11.278 --> 42:14.405
Until now, I haven't had
the manpower to take it.

42:14.406 --> 42:18.123
But now, with the men we have
here, I think it's possible,

42:18.148 --> 42:22.347
and if we could convince even half
of those slaves to join our fight,

42:22.700 --> 42:25.183
we might then actually be
in a position to take back...

42:25.184 --> 42:26.985
<i>FLINT: Too long.</i>

42:26.986 --> 42:29.521
What you're suggesting, we
don't have time for that.

42:30.597 --> 42:33.191
- Well, it'll take a few days...
- The governor may be on his heels,

42:33.192 --> 42:35.126
but he won't stay that way for long.

42:35.127 --> 42:38.196
It will be days, hours
maybe, before he finds a way

42:38.197 --> 42:41.866
to set his feet beneath
him and retrench.

42:41.867 --> 42:45.737
We need to strike
quickly, directly at Nassau

42:45.762 --> 42:47.910
with as many forces as
we can muster and today.

42:47.935 --> 42:50.239
- Hang on...
- We are two battered fighters

42:50.264 --> 42:52.810
at the end of a long fight.

42:52.811 --> 42:55.113
The next blow struck
may be a decisive one,

42:55.114 --> 42:56.514
and we have to be the one that strikes.

42:56.515 --> 42:57.914
Stop.

43:03.603 --> 43:06.767
I prepared these men to
follow Long John Silver

43:06.792 --> 43:08.716
upon his return.

43:09.779 --> 43:11.529
Now, if you assume that in his absence,

43:11.530 --> 43:14.532
that role now reverts to you...

43:14.533 --> 43:16.723
then you assume wrong.

43:16.748 --> 43:19.070
See, my men know your name,

43:19.071 --> 43:21.706
but you weren't the one who
recruited them into this.

43:21.990 --> 43:24.142
You weren't the one who led
them in those midnight raids

43:24.143 --> 43:26.311
in the Western plantations.

43:26.312 --> 43:28.880
You weren't the one
who has lived with them

43:28.881 --> 43:32.282
and drank with them and bled with them.

43:35.287 --> 43:37.422
So in the absence of Long John Silver,

43:37.423 --> 43:40.922
<i>the men will look to me, not you,</i>

43:40.947 --> 43:42.890
for answers to what happens next,

43:42.915 --> 43:45.498
and I will be the one to
give them those answers,

43:45.523 --> 43:47.022
not you.

43:48.534 --> 43:51.501
I have become so easily
set aside, have I?

43:54.567 --> 43:57.746
Do you have value to me? Yes.

43:57.801 --> 44:00.511
Would your skill in a
fight aid us in our efforts?

44:00.512 --> 44:02.312
Of course.

44:04.445 --> 44:07.452
But do we need you here?

44:07.453 --> 44:10.654
No. We do not.

44:12.062 --> 44:14.429
You're forgetting one thing.

44:14.760 --> 44:17.362
Somewhere on an island a
few days' journey from here

44:17.363 --> 44:21.766
is a chest filled with treasure
buried in a secret place,

44:21.767 --> 44:23.735
and of the three men
who know of that place,

44:23.736 --> 44:27.537
I may be the last one alive after today.

44:33.163 --> 44:36.608
Are you threatening to withhold
the location of the chest

44:36.633 --> 44:39.260
that every man here is counting upon

44:39.285 --> 44:42.882
to provide for Nassau's
treasury once we secure it

44:44.023 --> 44:47.525
solely so you can maintain
your own status here?

44:47.526 --> 44:51.796
There is an unthinkable
victory within our reach,

44:51.797 --> 44:53.331
and I will see this through

44:53.332 --> 44:56.466
by whatever means I have at my disposal.

44:57.236 --> 45:00.699
<i>This seems like the act
of a small man to you.</i>

45:01.307 --> 45:02.840
<i>Were he here, I'm sure,</i>

45:02.841 --> 45:05.143
Mr. Silver would make this all sound

45:05.144 --> 45:07.402
more agreeable to you.

45:08.047 --> 45:11.916
But without him, think what you like.

45:11.917 --> 45:14.684
My word will govern.

45:17.856 --> 45:19.789
<i>MADI: I know, too.</i>

45:23.851 --> 45:26.674
Three men know the
resting place of the chest,

45:26.699 --> 45:28.727
and one woman.

45:29.252 --> 45:31.919
He told it to me before we left home.

45:33.972 --> 45:35.973
<i>It would be preferable
if there were one voice</i>

45:35.974 --> 45:37.809
<i>to govern here tomorrow,</i>

45:37.810 --> 45:41.145
<i>but I don't think it's
going to be quite so simple.</i>

45:41.532 --> 45:44.263
There will be no pirate king here.

45:45.484 --> 45:47.817
Of that much, I am certain.

45:55.752 --> 45:57.611
[heartbeat]

46:35.529 --> 46:37.232
[distant explosions]

46:37.318 --> 46:39.396
[heartbeat speeding up]

46:45.005 --> 46:46.224
[distant screams]

47:08.008 --> 47:10.055
[heartbeat speeding up]

47:19.670 --> 47:23.233
[Gasping, explosions and shouting]

47:37.069 --> 47:38.428
[goat bleats]

48:05.424 --> 48:07.824
[Panicked grunting, goat bleating]

48:26.429 --> 48:29.084
[wood creaking]

48:56.041 --> 48:57.597
Are you through?

48:57.622 --> 48:59.343
Yes.

49:00.015 --> 49:01.395
Then go.

49:16.160 --> 49:19.027
When was the last time
you fought in a vanguard?

49:25.843 --> 49:29.585
He ain't never gonna see
you in that way, Teach.

49:30.075 --> 49:33.132
I know why you want him to,
but it ain't never gonna happen.

49:33.979 --> 49:36.213
You think that little
of me that I care so much

49:36.214 --> 49:37.748
how I'm seen in his eyes,

49:37.749 --> 49:40.284
I'd be willing to lose my life over it?

49:40.285 --> 49:42.452
Then why did you do it?

49:45.467 --> 49:48.092
When I was in that
carriage with the governor,

49:48.265 --> 49:50.494
when your horses first appeared,

49:50.773 --> 49:53.374
I had a chance to end it all.

49:53.436 --> 49:56.085
Had my hands round his neck.

49:57.406 --> 50:00.171
Had I done more in that moment,

50:00.172 --> 50:04.269
had I been more in that moment...

50:04.802 --> 50:06.901
Charles would still be here.

50:11.832 --> 50:14.118
The idea that he might
be looking down on me

50:14.119 --> 50:15.953
in this moment and find me not doing

50:15.954 --> 50:19.724
everything in my power to
see his death answered for,

50:19.725 --> 50:22.827
that is something I'm willing
to put my life at risk over,

50:22.975 --> 50:25.506
how I'm seen in his eyes.

50:26.670 --> 50:30.167
Charles Vane stood by us
when no one else would.

50:30.168 --> 50:33.771
Charles Vane risked his life for us.

50:33.772 --> 50:34.805
Charles Vane...

50:34.806 --> 50:36.806
Oh, fuck Charles Vane.

50:42.513 --> 50:44.724
I know how you felt about him.

50:45.910 --> 50:48.210
I felt the same way, and you know it.

50:49.471 --> 50:51.237
But he's dead.

50:53.684 --> 50:55.459
And I can't see what
fucking sense it makes

50:55.460 --> 50:57.261
to keep trying to make him happy.

50:57.262 --> 51:00.463
And all it's actually gonna
lead to is you joining him.

51:03.402 --> 51:06.848
If it had been me
strung up in that square,

51:06.873 --> 51:08.938
you'd feel the same way?

51:10.035 --> 51:11.656
I came here 'cause we all agreed

51:11.681 --> 51:14.015
we had a chance to take Nassau back,

51:14.512 --> 51:16.847
have a place of our own.

51:17.326 --> 51:19.677
I ain't here to prove anything!

51:20.469 --> 51:23.036
I ain't here to figure out who I am.

51:23.855 --> 51:26.023
And I sure as shit ain't
here to pretend a dead man

51:26.024 --> 51:28.359
might think better of me for it.

51:28.360 --> 51:32.489
We are all here towards the
end of retaking the island.

51:32.919 --> 51:35.499
In terms of motive,

51:35.500 --> 51:37.888
maybe we'll all just have to accept

51:37.913 --> 51:40.337
that we're driven by different things.

51:40.338 --> 51:41.691
Yeah?

51:41.716 --> 51:43.307
And what happens when those motives

51:43.308 --> 51:45.076
start demanding their own ends?

51:45.667 --> 51:47.111
<i>And this thing we're all a part of</i>

51:47.112 --> 51:48.566
<i>starts splitting right down the middle?</i>

51:48.591 --> 51:50.992
That isn't going to happen.

51:51.951 --> 51:53.873
It already is.

51:57.058 --> 51:59.107
What did he do?

52:01.505 --> 52:03.693
<i>BONNY: Set a course for Nassau...</i>

52:07.723 --> 52:10.490
<i>to send a message when we return...</i>

52:13.769 --> 52:16.069
<i>that this can all end...</i>

52:19.418 --> 52:22.652
<i>if the governor turns over
the one thing he wants.</i>

52:37.530 --> 52:39.864
When I made the choice to see
Charles' sentence carried out,

52:39.865 --> 52:43.043
I did not know what the
consequences would be.

52:44.165 --> 52:46.504
<i>I knew it was the only way
to protect our future here,</i>

52:46.505 --> 52:48.838
<i>to protect you, so I did it.</i>

52:51.176 --> 52:53.785
And when the backlash followed,

52:54.079 --> 52:56.027
the resentment over my
relationship with you,

52:56.052 --> 52:58.315
which I knew could only
be soothed by my pretending

52:58.316 --> 53:01.786
to have no influence
at all, I did that, too.

53:01.787 --> 53:05.156
I did all of it, contorted
myself into the role,

53:05.157 --> 53:07.792
mutilated myself so that it
would fit because I believed

53:07.793 --> 53:09.426
as long as you believed
I was your partner,

53:09.427 --> 53:11.162
it didn't matter what
anyone else believed.

53:11.163 --> 53:13.330
I've never believed you to
be anything less than that.

53:13.331 --> 53:14.799
Good, then can you tell me

53:14.800 --> 53:17.425
what the fuck just happened back there?

53:17.803 --> 53:20.271
I am asking her to
bear no more sacrifice

53:20.272 --> 53:22.840
than you or I or a dozen others.

53:22.841 --> 53:24.475
You're not asking her to bear anything.

53:24.476 --> 53:27.077
You have saddled her with
the cost of those trials.

53:27.078 --> 53:29.346
You might as well have stolen
the money to pay for it,

53:29.347 --> 53:32.399
but that is not what I am
talking about and you know it.

53:33.969 --> 53:36.387
To be my partner in
this, there are things

53:36.388 --> 53:37.672
that you are better off
letting me worry about.

53:37.697 --> 53:41.091
That is not what you said.
No more silent partners.

53:41.092 --> 53:43.093
We all bear the burden of this together.

53:43.094 --> 53:45.628
<i>What is it you are not telling me?</i>

53:47.666 --> 53:50.167
I don't want to be
protected. I don't want it.

53:50.310 --> 53:53.237
I need to know why you're behaving
as if victory is so far away

53:53.262 --> 53:55.927
when to me, it seems that
it is so close at hand.

54:13.058 --> 54:15.259
When I informed Sarah of my intent

54:15.260 --> 54:17.928
to formally end our marriage,

54:18.626 --> 54:21.587
I did not know what the
consequences would be.

54:22.501 --> 54:24.168
I didn't imagine they
would be significant.

54:24.169 --> 54:26.561
We'd barely spoken in years.

54:29.107 --> 54:30.840
Her reaction...

54:33.211 --> 54:36.112
was more significant
than I'd anticipated.

54:37.441 --> 54:38.973
What did she do?

54:44.173 --> 54:48.392
Her family intervened with
a few of my larger creditors

54:48.393 --> 54:53.397
and persuaded them to accelerate
my timetables for repayment.

54:53.774 --> 54:55.383
And if those creditors call the loans,

54:55.408 --> 54:57.914
it will force the others to follow suit.

55:00.515 --> 55:02.015
I would default.

55:03.718 --> 55:05.410
The courts would issue the warrant,

55:05.435 --> 55:09.061
and I would be a fugitive from the law.

55:11.049 --> 55:12.316
England is at war.

55:12.317 --> 55:14.318
There is no money from them
to support our efforts here.

55:14.319 --> 55:18.701
So I have had to assume substantial
private debts to do so...

55:19.739 --> 55:22.583
Debts which grow by the day.

55:23.051 --> 55:25.029
And as it would seem,
the only thing more costly

55:25.054 --> 55:27.587
than our defeats are our victories.

55:29.512 --> 55:31.268
Debts which will
require the swift return

55:31.269 --> 55:33.173
of commerce here if they
are ever to be repaid,

55:33.198 --> 55:35.906
commerce whose return at the moment

55:35.907 --> 55:37.907
seems so very far away.

55:40.987 --> 55:43.020
Why didn't you tell me?

55:46.518 --> 55:49.218
You are not a compromise to me.

55:54.092 --> 55:57.560
I do not regret what I did,
no matter the consequences.

55:58.991 --> 56:02.091
And I didn't want you to have
any reason to think that I did.

56:20.819 --> 56:23.020
Her family has the ability to do that,

56:23.021 --> 56:25.421
to manipulate your creditors so easily?

56:27.007 --> 56:29.429
Creditors respond to money.

56:29.761 --> 56:32.257
And they respond to influence.

56:32.999 --> 56:34.897
Her family has both.

56:37.407 --> 56:39.173
I understand.

56:41.806 --> 56:43.406
But...

56:45.043 --> 56:47.276
so does mine.

56:53.137 --> 56:55.496
[gentle waves]

57:12.137 --> 57:14.957
[panting]

57:45.303 --> 57:48.003
[Blow lands with sword, man cries out]

57:48.084 --> 57:51.943
♪ ♪

58:10.530 --> 58:13.788
[panicked grunting]

58:48.438 --> 58:50.871
<i>MAN: Long John Silver.</i>

58:52.153 --> 58:53.997
Welcome home.

